06972nam a22009015i 9781487514266DE-B159720220830111616.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220830t20182018onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875142667 a10.3138/97814875142662doi  a(DE-B1597)496353  a(OCoLC)1026407398  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aDK34.M39bM56 2018eb 7aHIS0320002bisacsh04a289.7/4722300aMinority Report :bMennonite Identities in Imperial Russia and Soviet Ukraine Reconsidered, 1789–1945 /ced. by Leonard G. Friesen. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (352 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTsarist and Soviet Mennonite Studies00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tA Note on Transliteration and Nomenclature -- tIntroduction -- tPart One: Overviews: New Approaches to Mennonite History -- t1. “Land of Opportunity, Sites of Devastation”: Notes on the History of the Borozenko Daughter Colony -- t2. Afforestation as Performance Art: Johann Cornies’ Aesthetics of Civilization -- tPart Two: Imperial Mennonite Isolationism Revisited -- t3. Mennonite Schools and the Russian Empire: The Transformation of Church-State Relations in Education, 1789–1917 -- t4. A Foreign Faith but of What Sort? The Mennonite Church and the Russian Empire, 1789–1917 -- t5. Mennonite Entrepreneurs and Russian Nationalists in the Russian Empire, 1830–1917 -- tPart Three: Mennonite Identities in Diaspora -- t6. Mennonite Identities in a New Land: Abraham A. Friesen and the Russian Mennonite Migration of the 1920s -- tPart Four: Mennonite Identities in the Soviet Cauldron -- t7. Collectivizing the Mutter Ansiedlungen: The Role of Mennonites in Organizing Kolkhozy in the Khortytsia and Molochansk German National Districts in Ukraine in the Late 1920s and Early 1930s -- t8. Kulak, Christian, and German: Ukrainian Mennonite Identities in a Time of Famine, 1932–1935 -- t9. Caught between Two Poles: Ukrainian Mennonites and the Trauma of the Second World War -- tAppendix: Dnipropetrovsk State University, Khortitsa ’99, and the Renaissance of Public (Mennonite) History in Ukraine -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe history of the Black Sea littoral, an area of longstanding interest to Russia, provides important insight into Ukraine as a contemporary state. In Minority Report, Leonard G. Friesen and the volume’s contributors boldly reassess Mennonite history in Imperial Russia and the former Soviet Ukraine. This volume engages scholars from Ukraine, Russia, and North America, and includes translated and accessible contributions by scholars from the Ukrainian-German Institute of Dnipropetrovsk State University. Minority Report is divided into four sections: New Approaches to Mennonite History; Imperial Mennonite Isolationism Revisited; Mennonite Identities in Diaspora; and Mennonite Identities in the Soviet Cauldron. An appendix is included which recounts for the first time the emergence of Mennonite public history in southern Ukraine after the collapse of the Soviet Union. The volume’s contributors reveal that far from being isolated from the larger society, Mennonites played an integral role in shaping the entire region. Minority Report successfully places Mennonite history within the recent historiographical insights offered by Ukrainian and Russian scholars and significantly enriches our understanding of minority relations in Soviet Ukraine.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 0aMennoniteszSoviet UnionxHistory. 0aUkrainianszSoviet UnionxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Russia & the Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh1 aBeznosov, Alexander, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb